Each woman interviewed said that the right to abortion she uses should not be restricted due to personal preference or how her religion teaches her to behave. All women interviewed said they were supportive of abortion for any reason throughout pregnancy.

Criminalization: Article 334 of the Moroccan Penal Code states that any person who takes an act of abortion, “knowing that she will cause the extermination of the human life inside the womb, shall be convicted for 3 to five years of imprisonment”.(42) Other penalties for abortion include six months imprisonment and a fine between 100 and 1000 dirhams.(43)

Abortions performed after 18 weeks of gestational age are punishable with imprisonment from 3 months to five years.

While abortion is illegal in Morocco, a 2019 Code of Ethics has made recourse to abortion procedures much easier for doctors. (44)

Criminalization policies seen outside of the African continent are not well suited to delivering justice in many African countries and pose a significant barrier to women accessing quality healthcare. In Morocco, laws imposing prison sentences with or without the death penalty for those performing abortions only compel women to resort to unsafe and untrained providers for medical advice and care. Laws criminalizing abortion also operate under the presumption that decisions to have an abortion are not taken within a rational examination of circumstances, but are instead criminal acts that do not need defendable arguments to justify their necessity.
